\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 13. T. macrophyllum} (Waldst. & Kit.) Schultz Bip.,{\i  Tanacet.} 53 (1844) ({\i Chrysanthemum macrophyllum} Waldst. & Kit., {\i Pyrethrum macrophyllum} (Waldst. & Kit.) Willd.). Perennial. Stems 40-100(-150) cm, usually solitary, simple or branched above. Leaves pinnatipartite to pinnatilobed, glabrous above, densely hairy beneath; cauline leaves subsessile, with 8-16 lanceolate, acute, doubly crenate segments. Capitula (20-)40-100(-150) in very dense, compound corymbs; involucre 4-7 mm in diameter. Ligulate florets white, female; ligules 2-4 mm. Achenes 1·6-2 mm, 5-ribbed; pappus a denticulate corona 0·2-0·3 mm.{\i  Mountain woods. From N.W. Jugoslavia and the E. Carpathians southwards to Macedonia; cultivated for ornament and locally naturalized in C. Europe.} Al Bu Gr Ju Rm [Cz Da Ge Hu Rs (W)].
